    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-28T15:00:00-05:00" n="233"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/145</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-28T20:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 28, 1917, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10.28 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8085. My telegram 8014, December 20, 9 a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d233fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1091">p. 1091</ref>.</note>
                    British are prepared to grant article 1 Swedish <hi rend="italic">modus
                        vivendi</hi> and release of the 22,000 bags of coffee mentioned in article
                    6. But [<hi rend="italic">And?</hi>] they will approve the request for
                    permission to import an additional 50,000 bags. Articles 7 and 8 are under
                    consideration. Present difficulties which could only be surmounted by proper
                    safeguards especially in regard to the leather which might be used by the Swedes
                    for manufacture of boots for Germany or release equivalent quantity, and the
                    cork bricks which would be used for storing meat which might subsequently be
                    released to the enemy.</p>
                <p>It is desirable that the other requirements in the Swedish <hi rend="italic"
                        >modus vivendi</hi> be met. Nothing prevents fullest extent possible in
                    order that a tonnage <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi> may be put promptly
                    into operation. The negotiations are in abeyance pending our decisions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
